 Service Pack. Otherwise, the Update program is unable to replace system files that are in use. If a file is in use when you install SP6, a dialog box appears prompting you to cancel the installation or skip the file copy. You should cancel the installation and then uninstall SP6. To uninstall SP6, see <a href="#2.5">Service Pack Uninstall</a>, later in this document.</p>
<p>
Also, to maximize recovery of the computer in the event of installation failure, you should do the following before installing SP6:
</p>
<ul>
<li>Update the system Emergency Repair Disk by using the Rdisk.exe command with the <b>/s</b> switch enabled.</li>
<li>Perform a full backup of the computer, including the registry files.</li>
<li>Disable any nonessential third-party drivers and services (that is, drivers and services that aren't required to start the computer).</li>
<li> For the updated versions of the file(s), contact the OEM that provided the driver or service.</li>
</ul></p>
<p>
To enable the uninstall option, run Update.exe. A subfolder named Uninstall is created in your Windows&nbsp;NT folder. This requires at least 120 megabytes (MB) of free space on the disk on which Windows&nbsp;NT&nbsp;4.0 is installed, 60 MB for the uninstall folder, and 60 MB for the Service Pack-updated system files.</p>

